definition: Nervous System
Status Description: Please use more detailed term within the hierarchy

definition: A feeling of falling down which can occur whether the person is standing, sitting or lying down.
Damage to the brain.
Hernia of brain substance and meninges through a congenital or traumatic opening of the skull.
A swelling in the brain caused by the presence of excessive fluid.
Unexpected increase in cerebral blood flow after carotid endarterectomy (CEA) or carotid artery stenting (CAS).
Abnormal enlargement of the cerebral ventricles.
Status Description: Term was modified on 21 January 2021 (old term: Cerebral Ventriculomeglia).

definition: The loss of cerebrospinal fluid into the surrounding tissues.
Changes in perception, thinking, or remembering.
A mental state characterized by a lack of clear and orderly thought and behavior.
Loss of intellectual abilities interfering with an individual's social and occupational functions.
Traumatic brain injury as a result of the action of a mechanical force on the head.
Sudden, involuntary skeletal muscular contractions of cerebral or brain stem origin.
A convulsion marked by alternating contracting and relaxing of the muscles.
A convulsion marked by prolonged contraction of the muscles.
Epilepsy caused or apparently caused by device. Do not use when epilepsy is a pre-existing condition.
A life-threatening condition characterised by a single prolonged seizure or a series of seizures without intervening full recovery of consciousness.
Status Description: Editorial change to the definition on 16 February 2021.

definition: Lower capacity to notice through one or more senses.
Higher capacity to notice through one or more senses.
A sensation of lightheadedness, unsteadiness, turning, spinning or rocking.
Impairment of verbal communication skills, often resulting from brain damage.
Inability to speak.
An acute inflammatory process affecting the brain parenchyma.
A functional and/or structural disorder of the brain that is acquired or congenital and characterised by mental and neurological symptoms.
Status Description: Editorial change to the definition on 16 February 2021.

definition: Pain in various parts of the head, not confined to the area of distribution of any nerve.
A disorder characterized by an abnormal increase of cerebrospinal fluid in the ventricles of the brain.
Bleeding within the cranium.
A level of awareness that can be described as consistently not responsive to stimuli.
A state of profound unconsciousness associated with markedly depressed cerebral activity.
Extremely weak; threatened with syncope.
A spontaneous, transient, loss of consciousness caused by insufficient blood supply to the brain.
Systematic and extensive loss or impairment of memory caused by organic or psychological factors. This may be temporary or permanent, and may involve old or recent memories.
A disorder characterized by acute inflammation of the meninges of the brain and/or spinal cord.
Neurological conditions resulting in abnormal voluntary or involuntary movement, which may impact the speed, fluency, quality and ease of movement.
Difficulty moving; distortion or impairment of voluntary movement, as in tic, spasm, or myoclonus.
Partial or complete loss of function of one or more muscles. It is usually caused by damage to the nervous system.
Paralysis of the legs and lower part of the body.
A slight or incomplete paralysis.
Paralysis of all four limbs.
The shaking movement of the whole body or just a certain part of it, often caused by problems of the neurons responsible for muscle action.
The occurrence of a single contraction or a series of contractions of a muscle.
Injury to nervous tissue.
Injury to optical nerve.
Injury to the central or peripheral nervous system.
Traumatic damage of the spinal cord.
Intense painful sensation along a nerve or group of nerves.
A disorder affecting the cranial nerves or the peripheral nervous system. It manifests with pain, tingling, numbness, and muscle weakness.
The loss of the sensation of feeling in an area of the body.
Injury to the peripheral nervous system.
Pain or discomfort caused by exposure of the dentin layer of tooth to thermal, tactile, or other stimuli.
A change from the patient's baseline sleeping pattern, in the hours slept and/or an alteration/dysfunction in the stages of sleep.
A term referring to disorders characterized by the disruption of normal speech. It includes stuttering, lisps, dysarthria and voice disorders.
A chronic adhesive arachnoiditis in the spinal arachnoid, with root and spinal cord symptoms similar to those caused by pressure from a tumor.
A sudden loss of neurological function secondary to hemorrhage or ischemia in the brain parenchyma due to a vascular event.
An acute neurological deficit caused by bleeding within the brain or between the brain and the skull.
An ischemic condition of the brain, producing a persistent focal neurological deficit in the area of distribution of the cerebral arteries.
conditions characterized by an alteration in the ability to or perception of touch.
Increased sensitivity to tactile stimulation.
Impairment of tactile sensitivity manifesting as partial loss of sensitivity to sensory stimuli.
Abnormal touch sensations, such as burning or prickling, that occur without an outside stimulus.
Conditions characterized by an alteration in taste function or perception
Status Description: Editorial change to the definition on 16 February 2021.

definition: Inability to taste.
Distortion of taste.
An involuntary, compulsive, repetitive stereotyped movement.
A brief attack (from a few minutes to an hour) of cerebral dysfunction of vascular origin, with no persistent neurological deficit.
Unintended reaction in nerve system caused by electrical stimulation.

The report describes a non-specific problem with the nervous system. Note: Please use "Appropriate Term / Code Not Available" if the report describes a specific injury but the relevant term does not exist.
Status Description: Term was added on 18 March 2020 for cases where the category of a health effect was reported but with no further details.

definition: Neurophysiological and psychological symptoms caused by sudden and unexpected loud noise.
A noise in the ears, such as ringing, buzzing, roaring or clicking in the absence of auditory stimulation.
Injury to the brain of a newborn infant occurring around the time of birth.
A reduction in the strength of one or more muscles.
Mental, Emotional and Behavioural Disorders
Status Description: Please use more detailed term within the hierarchy

definition: Excessive clenching of the jaw and grinding of the teeth.
Change from the affected person's usual emotional state.
Apprehension or uneasiness which may be accompanied by restlessness, tension, tachycardia, and dyspnea.
A condition marked by ongoing feelings of sadness, despair, loss of energy, diminished interest/pleasure and difficulty dealing with normal daily life.
A state of physiological or psychological stress that cannot be compensated for by normal adaptive measures.
A feeling of general discomfort or uneasiness, an out-of-sorts feeling.
A feeling of agitation. Tending to become frustrated or upset easily.
A false sensory perception in the absence of an external stimulus.
Characterized by a lack of vitality or energy.
Thoughts of taking one's own life.

term: Unspecified Mental, Emotional or Behavioural Problem
definition: The report describes a non-specific Mental, Emotional or Behavioural problem. Note: Please use "Appropriate Term / Code Not Available" if the report describes a specific problem but the relevant term does not exist.
Status Description: Term was added on 18 March 2020 for cases where the category of a health effect was reported but with no further details.

definition: Blood and Lymphatic System
Status Description: Please use more detailed term within the hierarchy

definition: A reduction in the number of red blood cells, the amount of hemoglobin, and/or the volume of packed red blood cells.
Anemia resulting from the premature destruction of the peripheral blood red cells.
A condition in which there is a deviation from or interruption of the normal coagulation properties of the blood.
A pathological process where the blood starts to coagulate throughout the whole body. This depletes the body of its platelets and coagulation factors, and there is an increased risk of hemorrhage.
Low blood platelet count.
Disruption of the integrity of the erythrocyte membrane causing release of hemoglobin.
An abnormally high circulating blood volume.
Status Description: Definition was modified on 21 January 2021 (Old definition: Too much fluid in the blood.). For details, see comment No. 2 of the Change Log.

definition: An abnormally low circulating blood volume.

The presence of pathogenic microorganisms in the blood stream causing a rapidly progressing systemic reaction that may lead to shock. Symptoms include fever, chills, tachycardia, and increased respiratory rate. It is a medical emergency that requires urgent medical attention.
A tumor-like collection of serum in the tissues.
The presence of an enlarged lymph node.
The white blood cell count is below the normal range
Status Description: Term was added on 18 March 2020 as an additional level 2 term for "Blood and Lymphatic System".

definition: The report describes a non-specific problem with the blood or lymphatic system. Note: Please use "Appropriate Term / Code Not Available" if the report describes a specific problem but the relevant term does not exist.
Status Description: Term was added on 18 March 2020 for cases where the category of a health effect was reported but with no further details.

definition: Higher or lower than normal values for the serum electrolytes; usually affecting Na, K, Cl, Ca, CO2, BUN.
Higher than normal levels of sodium in the circulating blood.
Lower than normal levels of sodium in the circulating blood.
Immune System
Status Description: Please use more detailed term within the hierarchy

definition: A disorder resulting from loss of function or tissue destruction of an organ or multiple organs, arising from humoral or cellular immune responses of the individual to his own tissue constituents.
A local or general reaction of an organism following contact with a specific allergen to which it has been previously exposed and to which it has become sensitized.
Progression of anaphylaxis into systemic shock, which is characterized by significant reduction in tissue perfusion which leads to hypoxia and hypotension, and can lead to death if untreated.
Resembling anaphylaxis
A regionally-limited response to an antigen, which may include inflammation, induration, erythema, pruritus or pain.
A deficiency of immune response or a disorder characterized by deficient immune response.

Indicates that antibodies directed against nuclear antigens have been detected. Almost invariably found in systemic lupus erythematosus and are frequently found in rheumatoid arthritis, scleroderma, Sjogren's Syndrome and mixed connective tissue disease.

The report describes a non-specific problem with the immune system. Note: Please use "Appropriate Term / Code Not Available" if the report describes a specific problem but the relevant term does not exist.
Status Description: Term was added on 18 March 2020 for cases where the category of a health effect was reported but with no further details.

definition: Vascular System
Status Description: Please use more detailed term within the hierarchy

definition: Unexpected increase in cerebral blood flow after carotid endarterectomy (CEA) or carotid artery stenting (CAS).
Bulging or ballooning in an area of an artery secondary to arterial wall weakening.
An aneurysm that has burst, resulting in hemorrhage into adjacent tissues.

A vascular disorder characterized by thickening and hardening of the walls of the arteries. Build-up of fatty material and calcium deposition in the arterial wall resulting in partial or complete occlusion of the arterial lumen.
The blockage of a blood vessel lumen by air or solid material such as blood clot or other tissues (e.g., adipose tissue, cancer cells) that have migrated from another anatomic site.
The presence of bubbles of air in the vascular system; occurrence is related to the entry of air into the venous circulation following trauma or surgery.
Type of embolism when lumen of vessel or ductus is occluded by part of device.
The obstruction of the pulmonary artery or one of its branches by an embolus, sometimes associated with infarction of the lung.
Occlusion of the lumen of a vessel by a thrombus that has migrated from a distal site via the blood stream.
The leakage of body fluid or cells from the vascular system to the surrounding tissues. This process occurs either by force or as a result of a pathologic reaction (e.g., inflammation).
A localized collection of blood, usually clotted, in an organ, space, or tissue, due to a break in the wall of a blood vessel.
The loss of blood from a ruptured blood vessel.

A flat discoloration of the skin or a mucous membrane, larger in area than a petechia, caused by the extravasation of blood. Discolouration under the skin caused by a bleed underneath. Typically a bruise.
Extensive loss of blood due to internal or external hemorrhage.
The measurement of the mean left atrial pressure, as measured by a catheter introduced into the distal pulmonary artery, is high.
The measurement of the mean left atrial pressure, as measured by a catheter introduced into the distal pulmonary artery, is low.
Status Description: Definition was modified on 21 January 2021 (Old definition: The measurement of the mean left pulmonary atrial pressure, as measured by a catheter introduced into the distal pulmonary artery, is low.). For details, see comment No. 3 of the Change Log.

definition: Lack of oxygen in tissues, commonly due to impaired blood supply to an area of the body, resulting in impairment of tissue oxygenation.
The formation of new blood vessels.
Damage to a blood vessel resulting from a full thickness disruption in the integrity of the vessel wall.
Damage to the venae cavae, pulmonary artery, pulmonary veins or aorta resulting from a full thickness disruption in the integrity of the vessel wall.
Inflammation of a vein.

The creation of hematoma outside the arterial wall following bleeding due to puncture of the arterial wall. Pseudoaneurysms can also occur in the heart chambers following myocardial infarction with rupture of the wall of the ventricle.
The formation of a blood clot in the lumen of a vessel or heart chamber.
Spontaneous or induced tear within the wall of a blood vessel.
Vasoconstriction involves narrowing of a blood vessel lumen due to smooth muscle contraction in the vessel wall and leads to decreased blood flow.
Widening of a blood vessel lumen due to smooth muscle relaxation in the vessel wall and leads to increased blood flow.

The report describes a non-specific problem with the vascular system. Note: Please use "Appropriate Term / Code Not Available" if the report describes a specific problem but the relevant term does not exist.
Status Description: Term was added on 18 March 2020 for cases where the category of a health effect was reported but with no further details.

definition: Circulatory insufficiency due to a decrease in the force of the cardiac contractions and / or the tone of the vascular walls
Bleeding from the bronchial wall and/or lung parenchyma.
Heart
Status Description: Please use more detailed term within the hierarchy

definition: Any variation from the normal rate or rhythm (which may include the origin of the impulse and/or its subsequent propagation) in the heart.
An electrocardiographic finding showing a state of cardiac standstill with no cardiac output and no ventricular depolarization.
Irregular heart rhythm, usually associated with a rapid rate, that is caused by abnormal electrical activity within the atrial.
A rapid heart rate, associated with a regular rhythm, that is caused by abnormal electrical activity within the atria.
An abnormally slow heart rate. Thresholds for different age, gender, and patient populations exist.
A cardiac beat originating from an abnormal site. These changes lead to extra or dropped heartbeats.
An interference with the normal conduction of electrical impulses that control activity of the heart muscle.
An electrocardiographic finding of three or more consecutive complexes of ventricular origin. The QRS complexes are wide and have an abnormal morphology. (CDISC)
A pulse that beats at irregular intervals.
Abnormally high heart rate. Thresholds for different age, gender, and patient populations exist.
Arrhythmia characterized by chaotic contractions of the ventricular muscle.
The sudden cessation of productive cardiac activity in an individual who becomes unresponsive, without normal breathing and no signs of circulation.
Increase from the normal levels of cardiac enzymes.
The presence of an acquired hole in the heart.

Acute compression of the heart caused by increased intrapericardial pressure due to the accumulation of blood or fluid in the pericardium from rupture of the heart or great vessels, penetrating trauma, or progressive effusion.
A disease of the heart muscle.
Circulatory insufficiency due to a decrease in the force of the cardiac contractions and / or the tone of the vascular walls
A tear located on a leaflet of a heart valve that prevents its complete closing, which can result in valvular dysfunction.
Weak or absent palpable pulse due to decreased arterial pulse pressure.
Inflammation of the endocardium.
Inability of the heart to pump blood adequately to fill tissue metabolic requirements or the ability to do so only at an elevated filling pressure.

A disorder of cardiac function caused by insufficient blood flow to the muscle tissue of the heart. The decreased blood flow may be due to narrowing of the coronary arteries, to obstruction by a thrombus, or less commonly, to diffuse narrowing of arterioles and other small vessels within the heart. Severe interruption of the blood supply to the myocardial tissue may result in necrosis of cardiac muscle (myocardial infarction).
Chest pain resulting from inadequate oxygen delivery for the needs of the myocardium.
A condition which occurs when blood flow decreases or stops to a part of the heart, causing damage to the heart muscle.
A below normal volume of blood pumped from the right or left ventricle of the heart per unit time.
A rupture in the mitral valve tissue due to traumatic or pathologic processes.
A bruise to the heart.
Thickening of the myocardium often due to chronic pressure overload.
Inflammation of the muscle tissue of the heart.
An electrocardiographic finding of a change in cardiac electrical activity.
Fluid collection within the pericardial sac, usually due to inflammation.
Inflammation of the pericardium.
Dysfunction of one of the cardiac valves, with incomplete valve closure or damage to a valve leaflet resulting in valvular backflow.
Incomplete closure or damage to a valve leaflet of the aortic valve, resulting in aortic valve backflow.
Incomplete closure or damage to a valve leaflet of the mitral valve, resulting in mitral valve backflow.
Incomplete closure or damage to a valve leaflet of the pulmonary valve, resulting in pulmonary valve backflow.
Incomplete closure or damage to a valve leaflet of the tricuspid valve, resulting in tricuspid valve backflow.
Obstruction of flow across a heart valve due to immobility of the leaflets and/or a restricted orifice.
Obstruction of flow across a aortic heart valve due to immobility reduced elasticity of the leaflets and/or a restricted orifice.
Obstruction of flow across a mitral heart valve due to immobility reduced elasticity of the leaflets and/or a restricted orifice.
Obstruction of flow across a pulmonary heart valve due to immobility reduced elasticity of the leaflets and/or a restricted orifice.
Obstruction of flow across a tricuspid heart valve due to immobility reduced elasticity of the leaflets and/or a restricted orifice.
The report describes a non-specific problem with the heart. Note: Please use "Appropriate Term / Code Not Available" if the report describes a specific problem but the relevant term does not exist.
Status Description: Term was added on 18 March 2020 for cases where the category of a health effect was reported but with no further details.

definition: Signs or symptoms which may be indicative of distress to a fetus, which may include repetitive variable decelerations, fetal tachycardia or bradycardia, late decelerations, or low biophysical profile.
Respiratory System
Status Description: Please use more detailed term within the hierarchy

definition: The obstruction of the pulmonary artery or one of its branches by an embolus, sometimes associated with infarction of the lung.

Progressive and life-threatening pulmonary distress in the absence of an underlying pulmonary condition, usually following major trauma or surgery. Cases of neonatal respiratory distress syndrome are not included in this definition.
Blockage of air flow in the respiratory tract.
Transient cessation of respiration.
The entry of foreign material past the trachea, and into the lower respiratory tract.
Inflammation of the lungs due to the inhalation of solid or liquid material.
A chronic respiratory disease manifested as difficulty breathing due to the narrowing of bronchial passageways.
Bleeding from the bronchial wall and/or lung parenchyma.
An acute or chronic inflammatory process affecting the bronchi.
Sudden contraction of the smooth muscles of the bronchial wall.
Interference with respiration by obstruction of the larynx or trachea.
Status Description: Editorial change to the definition on 16 February 2021.

definition: A chronic and progressive lung disorder characterized by the loss of elasticity of the bronchial tree and the air sacs, destruction of the air sacs wall, thickening of the bronchial wall, and mucous accumulation in the bronchial tree. The pathologic changes result in the disruption of the air flow in the bronchial airways. Signs and symptoms include shortness of breath, wheezing, productive cough, and chest tightness. The two main types of chronic obstructive pulmonary disease are chronic obstructive bronchitis and emphysema.
A condition characterized by increase beyond normal in the size of air spaces distal to the terminal bronchioles, either from dilatation of the alveoli or from destruction of their walls.
A sudden, often repetitive, spasmodic contraction of the thoracic cavity, resulting in violent release of air from the lungs, and usually accompanied by a distinctive sound.
Decrease in the maximum flow rate generated during a forceful exhalation, starting from full lung inflation.
An increase of the greatest rate of flow that can be achieved during forced expiration beginning with the lungs fully inflated.
Abnormal decrease of rate of breathing.
Abnormal increase of rate of breathing.
An uncomfortable sensation of difficulty breathing. It may present as an acute or chronic sign of an underlying respiratory or heart disorder.
Nose bleed.
A decrease in the fraction of the forced vital capacity that is exhaled in a specific number of seconds.
An increase in the fraction of the forced vital capacity that is exhaled in a specific number of seconds.
Coughing up blood from the respiratory tract.
A collection of blood in the pleural cavity.
An involuntary contraction of the diaphragm against closed vocal cords, producing the hic sound.
Abnormally prolonged, rapid, and deep breathing.
A state in which there is a reduced amount of air entering the pulmonary alveoli.
A deficiency in the amount of oxygen reaching the tissues.
Displacement of structures in the thoracic cavity in one direction due to increased pleural pressure on the contralateral side.
Blockage of the nasal passages.
Abnormal permanent enlargement of the lung air spaces distal to terminal bronchiole not resulted from wall destruction, e.g. due to loss of opposite lung.
Inflammation of the throat most often caused by viral and bacterial infections.
Increased amounts of fluid within the pleural cavity. Symptoms include shortness of breath, cough, and chest pain.
An accumulation of pus in the pleural space
An acute and/or chronic inflammation focally or diffusely affecting the lung parenchyma.
Acute inflammation of the walls of the terminal bronchioles.
Abnormal presence of air in the pleural cavity.
Impaired or abnormal functioning of the pulmonary system causing multiple pulmonary issues.
Accumulation of fluid in the lung tissues causing disturbance of the gas exchange that may lead to respiratory failure.
Increased pressure within the pulmonary circulation due to lung or heart disorder.
Localized necrosis of lung tissue caused by obstruction of the arterial blood supply, most often due to pulmonary embolism.
A condition in which the blood pH is less than normal, secondary to impaired gas exchange.
A condition in which the blood pH is greater than normal, secondary to impaired gas exchange.
Cessation of breathing function.
The significant impairment of gas exchange within the lungs resulting in hypoxia, hypercarbia, or both, to the extent that organ tissue perfusion is severely compromised.
Impairment of gas exchange within the lungs secondary to a disease process, neoplasm, or trauma, possibly resulting in hypoxia, hypercarbia, or both.
An infectious disease affecting the respiratory tract.
A rupture in the sinus tissue due to traumatic or pathologic processes.
A symptom consisting of the involuntary expulsion of air from the nose.
Any kind of inflammatory process of the tonsils, pharynx, or/and larynx characterized by pain in swallowing.
Condition where there are a greater number of inhalations relative to the number of exhalations.
Interference with respiration by compression of the larynx, laryngopharynx or trachea, as well as of the carotid arteria or jugular veins.
Status Description: Editorial change to the definition on 16 February 2021.

definition: A condition that requires mechanical life support due to inability to breath effectively to maintain normal levels of oxygen and carbon dioxide in the body.
A symptom and finding during physical examination, characterized by high-pitched, whistling sound during breathing. it results from narrowing or obstruction of the respiratory airways.

The report describes a non-specific problem with the respiratory system. Note: Please use "Appropriate Term / Code Not Available" if the report describes a specific problem but the relevant term does not exist.
Status Description: Term was added on 18 March 2020 for cases where the category of a health effect was reported but with no further details.

definition: A condition of the newborn marked by dyspnea with cyanosis.

A high level of the degree to which oxygen is bound to hemoglobin given as a percentage calculated by dividing the maximum oxygen capacity into the actual oxygen content and multiplying by 100. Oxygen saturation usually is measured using pulse oximetry.

A low level of the degree to which oxygen is bound to hemoglobin given as a percentage calculated by dividing the maximum oxygen capacity into the actual oxygen content and multiplying by 100. Oxygen saturation usually is measured using pulse oximetry.
Eye
Status Description: Please use more detailed term within the hierarchy

definition: A tear in the capsular bag housing the lens.

Partial or complete opacity of the crystalline lens of one or both eyes that decreases visual acuity and eventually results in blindness. Some cataracts appear in infancy or in childhood, but most develop in older individuals. (Sternberg Diagnostic Surgical Pathology, 3rd ed.)
Edema of the mucous membrane of the eyeball and eyelid lining.
Inflammation of the conjunctiva of the eye.
Clouding of the middle area of the cornea, usually as a result of scarring due to infection, injury, or inflammation.
Inability to maintain corneal integrity; or corneal edema resulting from failure of the corneal endothelium to maintain detumescence.
Hazy, swollen cornea.
Fluid from the aqueous humor enters the corneal stroma and causes swelling.
Corneal edema of inflammatory origin associated with contact lens wear and morphologically characterized by presence of epithelial microcysts.

Very small, round vesicles containing fluid and cellular debris observed on the surface of the cornea under slit lamp examination in some types of corneal dystrophy and in wearers of extended wear lenses.
Discrete, small lesions present in the cornea as a result of corneal inflammation and, in some cases, after soft contact lens wear especially extended-wear lenses.
Superficial vascularization of the cornea with infiltration of granulation tissue.
A rupture in the corneal tissue due to traumatic or pathologic processes.
Replacement of corneal tissue with scar tissue as a result of injury to the deeper layers of the cornea.
Complications of intraocular lens surgery; usually refers to intraocular lens contact with cornea, can be intermittent or chronic.
Area of epithelial tissue loss from corneal surface; associated with inflammatory cells in the cornea and anterior chamber.

A syndrome characterized by dryness of the cornea and conjunctiva. It is usually caused by a deficiency in tear production. Symptoms include a feeling of burning eyes and a possible foreign body presence in the eye.
Inflammation of the intraocular fluids or tissues usually with microbial organisms.
Profuse lacrimation.
An infection of any part of the eye, including the eyelid.
Infection within the eye.
Damage to the eye.
Injury to the epithelium of the cornea.
Burn injury, including chemical burn, to any part of the eye.
Separation of the inner retina layers from the underlying pigment epithelium.
Damage to the retina due to toxicity, exposure to bright lights, or trauma.
A usually small tearing of the retina occurring when the vitreous separates from the retina. It may lead to retinal detachment.
Detachment of the vitreous humor from the retina.
Painful sensation in the eye.
Feeling of grittiness or having something in the eye; frequently caused by a foreign body.
Increased pressure in the eyeball due to obstruction of the outflow of aqueous humor.
Hazy ring around bright lights seen by some patients with refractive error or optical defects, e.g. cataracts, or corneal swelling.
Hemorrhage within the anterior chamber of the eye; bloodshot.
An accumulation of pus in the anterior chamber of the eye.
Decrease of pressure of the intraocular fluid in the eye.
Increase of pressure of the intraocular fluid in the eye.
Inflammation of the iris.
Inflammation of the cornea.
Keratitis due to infection by acanthamoeba.
Status Description: The term and definition were modified on 21 January 2021 to use the following spelling: Acanthamoeba.

definition: Accumulation of intraretinal fluid and protein in the macula, which may result in swelling and decreased central vision.

Ocular pain which may be very intense, accompanied by corneal epithelium damage, conjunctival injection, lacrimation, blepharospasm, photophobia and hazy vision following corneal edema caused by overwear of contact lenses, principally the PMMA type.
An obstruction of the pupil.
Lay term applied to any condition with dilation of conjunctival or ciliary blood vessels; innumerable causes.
Degeneration of the retina.
An acute postoperative inflammatory reaction in which a noninfectious substance enters the anterior segment and induces toxic damage to the intraocular tissues.
Status Description: Editorial change to the definition on 16 February 2021.

definition: Clinical triad of uveitis, glaucoma, and hyphema (UGH), especially associated with the insertion of an anterior chamber intraocular lens (IOL).
Inflammation of the uvea.
An interference to normal eyesight without necessarily affecting visual acuity.
The perception of sudden or brief bursts of light.
An objective visual sensation that appears with the eyes closed and in the absence of visual light.
Spots or stringy shapes in vision, often caused by deposits, aggregates, or cell fragments in the vitreous humor or lens.
Decreased ability to see to a degree that requires corrective measures
The loss of visual acuity (sharpness of vision).
Severely reduced visual acuity that cannot be corrected, or total loss of vision.
Blood extravasation in the vitreous humor.
loss or prolapse of vitreous gel.
Inflammatory intraocular reaction with clouding and cells in vitreous; often accompanies inflammation of ciliary body, iris, choroid, or retina.
Rupture of the fibrous strands connecting the ciliary body with the crystalline lens of the eye (usually at the time of cataract surgery).
Status Description: Editorial change to the definition on 16 February 2021.

definition: The report describes a non-specific problem with the eye(s) or vision. Note: Please use "Appropriate Term / Code Not Available" if the report describes a specific problem but the relevant term does not exist.
Status Description: Term was added on 18 March 2020 for cases where the category of a health effect was reported but with no further details.

definition: Ear and Labyrinth
Status Description: Please use more detailed term within the hierarchy

definition: Neurophysiological and psychological symptoms caused by sudden and unexpected loud noise.
Injury to the hearing mechanisms within the inner ear, caused by excessively loud noise.
Partial or complete loss of the ability to detect or understand sounds resulting from damage to the outer, middle, or inner ear structures.
A condition in which a person partially loses the ability to hear sounds in one or both ears.
A condition in which a person completely loses the hearing in one or both ears.
A noise in the ears, such as ringing, buzzing, roaring or clicking in the absence of auditory stimulation.

A feeling of movement, a sensation as if the external world were revolving around the person or as if they were revolving in space (subjective vertigo). Vertigo is medically distinct from dizziness, lightheadedness, and unsteadiness.

The report describes a non-specific problem with the ear or labyrinth. Note: Please use "Appropriate Term / Code Not Available" if the report describes a specific problem but the relevant term does not exist.
Status Description: Term was added on 18 March 2020 for cases where the category of a health effect was reported but with no further details.

definition: An abnormality that affects hearing within the first month after birth.
Complete loss of the ability to detect or understand sounds present in an infant within its first month after birth.
Partial loss of the ability to detect or understand sounds present in an infant within its first month after birth.
Gastrointestinal System
Status Description: Please use more detailed term within the hierarchy

definition: The condition of the abdomen being enlarged or swollen from internal pressure.
Painful sensation in the abdominal region.
Failure of the smooth muscle fibers of the gastrointestinal tract to relax at any one point of junction of one part with another.
Accumulation of fluid in the peritoneal cavity. The fluid may be serous, hemorrhagic, or the result of tumor metastasis to the peritoneum.
A thermal injury to the bowels.
A rupture in the wall of the small or large intestine due to traumatic or pathologic processes.
Irregular and infrequent or difficult evacuation of the bowels.
Frequent, watery bowel movements.
A symptom referring to difficult and or painful swallowing.
To belch, the casting of upwind from the stomach.
Gas or air in the gastrointestinal tract.
Inflammation of the stomach.
Thermal, chemical or radiation injury to stomach or esophagus.
Bleeding originating from any part of the gastrointestinal tract.

Flow in the opposite direction from normal, as the casting up of undigested food or gas from the stomach, or the backward flowing of blood into the heart, or between the chambers of the heart when a valve is incompetent.
Vomiting blood.
Bleeding within the abdominal cavity.
A torn, ragged, mangled wound, or an accidental cut of esophagus.
Abnormally dark tarry feces containing blood, usually from gastrointestinal bleeding.
Upper abdominal discomfort associated with an urge to vomit.
Inflammation of the pancreas.
The presence of a hole or other type of opening in the esophageal wall through which the contents of the esophagus can pass into the mediastinum.
A cut or tear of the peritoneum.
Inflammation of the peritoneum due to infection by bacteria or fungi.
Abdominal discomfort with retrosternal pain usually associated with gastroesophageal reflux.
Leakage due to breakdown of a rectal anastomosis.
Bleeding originating in the retroperitoneal area.
A non-neoplastic or neoplastic (benign or malignant) disorder involving a salivary gland.
The condition of not having enough saliva to keep the mouth moist.
Excessive saliva production.
Narrowing or tightening of the esophagus
The formation of sores or a break in the wall of the stomach.
Inflammation of the oral mucosa.
Inflammation of the tongue.
Forceful ejection of the contents of the stomach through the mouth.

Shivering or moderate tremors of the body often accompanied by a cold sensation.
A bluish or purplish discoloration of the skin and mucous membranes resulting from a reduced amount of oxygenated hemoglobin in the blood.
Lack of desire for food.
Intense desire for food.
An alteration of appearance, shape, size or alignment.
Accumulation of extraneous inorganic matter in tissues or cavities.
Deposition of calcium salt in the tissues.
Profuse sweating.
A feeling of mental or physical uneasiness, pain, or distress.
A state of generalized weakness with a pronounced inability to summon sufficient energy to accomplish daily activities.
Extreme fatigue; the inability to respond to stimuli.
Status Description: Editorial change to the definition on 16 February 2021.

definition: The formation of fibrous tissue.
A fibrous band of tissue that connects normally separate body regions.
Abnormal epithelial-lined communication between two anatomical structures.
Flow or leakage of fluid other than blood, from an orifice, wound or tissue.
A flow or draining of pus or exudate from an orifice or wound.
Status Description: Editorial change to the definition on 16 February 2021.

definition: An inflammatory reaction evoked by the presence of an exogenous material in the tissues.
An inflammatory reaction usually caused by infectious organisms, foreign bodies, or cholesterol deposits. It is characterized by the presence of epithelioid histiocytes and chronic inflammation.
Loss of hair usually from the scalp that may result in bald spots or spread to the entire scalp or epidermis.
The protrusion of part of an organ or fibroadipose tissue through an opening or weakened area.
Blood pressure that is abnormally high.
Blood pressure that is abnormally low.
The presence of an increased amount of blood in a part or organ; engorgement.
An abnormal increase in the number of cells in an organ or a tissue with consequent enlargement.
Involuntary passage of feces and/or urine from the body.
Inability to control voluntary passage of feces from the body.
Inability to control voluntary passage of urine from the body.
Permeation of foreign substances into tissues or cells.
A localized physical condition in which part of the body becomes reddened, swollen, or hot and often painful.
The pathologic death of cells or of a portion of tissue or organ resulting from irreversible damage.
Blockage or closing of the normal flow of the contents of an anatomical passageway.
A splitting open or rupture of an internal organ with the exposure or discharge of its content.
An unpleasant sensory and emotional experience that is associated with actual or potential tissue damage or described in such terms.
Pain in various parts of the head, not confined to the area of distribution of any nerve.
Painful sensation in the eye.
Painful sensation in the abdominal region.
Pain sensation originating from a muscle or group of muscles.
Pain in the neck area.
Pain that is associated with an external artificial replacement device.
Status Description: Definition was modified on 21 January 2021 to correct a typo in "artificial" (Old definition: Pain that is associated with an external ariticial replacement device.)

definition: Pain localized to the site of the implanted device.
Continuing discomfort due to a lack or failure of a medical approach to treat pain.
Pain occurring during a surgical operation.
Pain in the chest.
Unhealthy, pale or white appearance of the face.
Lack or absence of balanced proportions between parts or organs of the body.
A condition in which an organ or body tissue drops or bulges out of place.
The drooping or downward displacement of a body part.

term: Reaction to Medicinal Component of Device
definition: Any local or systemic adverse reaction to the medicinal component of a combination product.
A life-threatening condition that requires immediate medical intervention. It is characterized by reduced blood flow that may result in damage of multiple organs.
Status Description: Editorial change to the definition on 16 February 2021.

definition: Progression of anaphylaxis into systemic shock, which is characterized by significant reduction in tissue perfusion which leads to hypoxia and hypotension, and can lead to death if untreated.
Shock resulting from primary failure of the heart in its pumping function, as in myocardial infarction, severe cardiomyopathy, or mechanical obstruction or compression of the heart.
A hypoglycemic reaction to overdosage of insulin, a skipped meal, or strenuous exercise in an insulin-dependent diabetic.
Shock resulting from insufficient blood volume for the maintenance of adequate cardiac output, blood pressure and tissue perfusion.

Shock resulting from neurogenic vasodilation, which can be produced by cerebral trauma or hemorrhage, spinal cord injury, deep general or spinal anesthesia, or toxic central nervous system depression.
A state of acute circulatory failure resulting from organ injury or damage in response to infection that results in dangerously low blood pressure.
Narrowing or stricture of a vessel, duct or canal.
The reoccurrence of stenosis after it has been treated.
Enlargement or expansion in size of a body part from injury or inflammation.
A swelling in the brain caused by the presence of excessive fluid.
Accumulation of fluid in the lung tissues causing disturbance of the gas exchange that may lead to respiratory failure.
Hazy, swollen cornea.
Fluid from the aqueous humor enters the corneal stroma and causes swelling.
Corneal edema of inflammatory origin associated with contact lens wear and morphologically characterized by presence of epithelial microcysts.
Accumulation of intraretinal fluid and protein in the macula, which may result in swelling and decreased central vision.
Rapid swelling of the deep layers of the skin due to transient vascular leakage of serous fluid.
accumulation of fluid in tissues perfused by the peripheral vascular system.
An open sore on an external or internal surface of the body caused by a break in the skin or mucous membrane that fails to heal.
A complication in which the wound splits or separates after being surgically closed.
The presence of two distinct capsular layers around an implant with an intercapsular space

definition: Complete impairment of two or more organs or organ systems. Also known as multiple organ failure.

definition: Others
Status Description: Please use more detailed term within the hierarchy

definition: Health effect appears to have occurred but there is not yet enough information available to classify the clinical signs, symptoms and conditions.

The clinical signs, symptoms and conditions are not adequately described by any other term. Note: this code must not be used unless there is no other feasible code. The preferred term should be documented when submitting an adverse event report. This information will be used to determine if a new term should be added to the code table.

term: No Clinical Signs, Symptoms or Conditions
definition: No patient involvement or, no observable clinical symptoms or a change in symptoms is identified in the patient.
